05708nam a22006975i 9780822395478DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223954787 a10.1515/97808223954782doi  a(DE-B1597)552299  a(OCoLC)1224277982  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.4/6122300aMedical Anthropology at the Intersections :bHistories, Activisms, and Futures /ced. by Marcia C. Inhorn, Emily A. Wentzell. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b9 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Medical Anthropology at the Intersections -- tPART I. HISTORIES -- tONE Grafting Together Medical Anthropology, Feminism, and Technoscience -- tTWO Getting at Anthropology through Medical History -- tTHREE Making Peasants Protestant and Other Projects -- tPART II. QUERIES -- tFOUR That Obscure Object of Global Health -- tFIVE Medical Anthropology and Mental Health -- tSIX From Genetics to Postgenomics and the Discovery of the New Social Body -- tPART III. ACTIVISM -- tSEVEN Anthropology and the Study of Disability Worlds -- tEIGHT Medical Anthropology and Public Policy -- tNINE Critical Intersections and Engagements -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this important collection, prominent scholars who helped to establish medical anthropology as an area of study reflect on the field's past, present, and future. In doing so, they demonstrate that medical anthropology has developed dynamically, through its intersections with activism, with other subfields in anthropology, and with disciplines as varied as public health, the biosciences, and studies of race and ethnicity. Each of the contributors addresses one or more of these intersections. Some trace the evolution of medical anthropology in relation to fields including feminist technoscience, medical history, and international and area studies. Other contributors question the assumptions underlying mental health, global public health, and genetics and genomics, areas of inquiry now central to contemporary medical anthropology. Essays on the field's engagements with disability studies, public policy, and gender and sexuality studies illuminate the commitments of many medical anthropologists to public-health and human-rights activism. Essential reading for all those interested in medical anthropology, this collection offers productive insight into the field and its future, as viewed by some of the world's leading medical anthropologists.Contributors. Lawrence Cohen, Didier Fassin, Faye Ginsburg, Marcia C. Inhorn, Arthur Kleinman, Margaret Lock, Emily Martin, Lynn M. Morgan, Richard Parker, Rayna Rapp, Merrill Singer, Emily A. Wentzell  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMedical anthropologyxResearch. 0aMedical anthropologyxStudy and teaching. 0aMedical anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFassin, Didier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsburg, Faye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInhorn, Marcia C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInhorn, Marcia C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKleiman, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLock, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov